{"title_page": "Center for a New American Security", "text_new": "{{infobox Organization\n| name = Center for a New American Security\n| image = CNAS logo.svg\n| size = \n| abbreviation = CNAS\n| motto = 'Bold. Innovative. Bipartisan'\n| formation = {{start date and age|2007}}\n| type = [[Public policy]] [[think tank]]\n| tax_id = 20-8084828\n| headquarters = 1152 15th St., Ste. 950\n| location = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| leader_title = CEO\n| leader_name = Richard Fontaine<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cnas.org/people/richard-fontaine | title=People | date= | website=Center for a New American Security | accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n| budget = Revenue: $8,789,410<br>Expenses: $7,228,402<br>([[Fiscal year|FYE September 2015]])<ref name=\"Charity ratings\">{{cite web | url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/files.cnas.org/CNAS_Form990_2015a.pdf | title=Center for a New American Security | date=30 September 2016 | website=Amazon Web Services | accessdate=27 February 2017 }}</ref>\n| website = {{url|https://www.cnas.org|CNAS.org}}\n}}[[File:Petraeus1.jpg|thumb|right|GEN [[David Petraeus]] at CNAS's annual conference, June 2009]]\n\nThe '''Center for a New American Security''' ('''CNAS''') is a [[Washington, D.C.]]-based [[think tank]] established in 2007 by co-founders [[Mich\u00e8le Flournoy]] and [[Kurt M. Campbell]]. It specializes in the [[United States]]' [[national security]] issues.  CNAS's stated mission is to \"develop strong, pragmatic and principled national security and defense policies that promote and protect American interests and values.\"<ref>Center for a New American Security, [http://www.cnas.org/about About CNAS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100228145753/http://www.cnas.org/about |date=2010-02-28 }}</ref> CNAS focuses on [[terrorism]] and [[irregular warfare]], the future of the [[U.S. armed forces|U.S. military]], the emergence of [[Asia]] as a global power center, and the national security implications of [[natural]] [[resource consumption]]. Former [[United States Deputy Secretary of State|Deputy Secretary of State]] [[James Steinberg]] called CNAS \"an indispensable feature on the Washington landscape.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/s/d/2009/129686.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091130033804/http://www.state.gov/s/d/2009/129686.htm |archivedate=2009-11-30 }} </ref>  Speaking at the CNAS annual conference in June 2009, [[U.S. Central Command]] Commander GEN [[David Petraeus]] observed that \"CNAS has, in a few years, established itself as a true force in think tank and policy-making circles.\"<ref>Center for a New American Security, [http://www.cnas.org/files/newsletter/CNAS%20About%20Us.pdf 'About the Center for a New American Security] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403123718/http://www.cnas.org/files/newsletter/CNAS%20About%20Us.pdf |date=2015-04-03 }}, 2012.</ref>\n\nThe administration of President [[Barack Obama]] hired several CNAS employees for key jobs.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/05/AR2009060501967.html | work=The Washington Post | title=Carlos Lozada -- Setting Priorities for the Afghan War | date=June 7, 2009 | accessdate=April 28, 2010}}</ref> Founders [[Mich\u00e8le Flournoy]] and [[Kurt M. Campbell|Kurt Campbell]] formerly served as the [[Undersecretary of Defense for Policy]] and the [[Assistant Secretary of State for East Asian and Pacific Affairs]], respectively. In June 2009 ''The Washington Post'' suggested, \"In the era of Obama... the Center for a New American Security may emerge as Washington's go-to think tank on military affairs.\"<ref name=\"post\" />  CNAS scholars have included [[John Nagl]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/01/15/AR2008011503359.html|title=High-Profile Officer Nagl to Leave Army, Join Think Tank | work=The Washington Post | first=Thomas E. | last=Ricks | date=January 16, 2008 | accessdate=April 28, 2010}}</ref> [[David Kilcullen]], [[Andrew Exum]], [[Thomas E. Ricks (journalist)|Thomas E. Ricks]], [[Robert D. Kaplan]],<ref>Center for a New American Security, [http://www.cnas.org/node/71 Robert Kaplan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315080012/http://www.cnas.org/node/71 |date=2011-03-15 }}.</ref> and [[Marc Lynch]]. CNAS is led by CEO [[Victoria Nuland]], who served as the Assistant Secretary of State for European and Eurasian Affairs under Secretary of State [[John Kerry]].\n\nCNAS is relatively small, with around 30 employees and a budget under $6 million.<ref name=\"wsj\">Yochi J. Dreazen, [http://www.livemint.com/2008/11/17175320/Obama-dips-into-think-tank-for.html \"Obama dips into think tank for talent\"], ''The Wall Street Journal'', 18 November 2008</ref> Among the organizations top donors include [[Northrop Grumman Aerospace Systems]], [[Open Society Foundation]], [[Airbus Group]], [[The Boeing Company]], [[Chevron Corporation]], [[Lockheed Martin Corporation]], [[Raytheon Company]], the [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office]],  the United States government, [[BAE Systems]], [[BP America]] and [[Exxon Mobil Corporation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnas.org/support-cnas/cnas-supporters|title=CNAS Supporters|website=www.cnas.org}}</ref>\n\nIn a speech to the [[United States Military Academy]] at [[West Point]] on February 25, 2011, Secretary of Defense [[Robert Gates]] quoted CNAS President [[John Nagl]] and Senior Advisor and Senior Fellow Lieutenant General [[David Barno]], USA (Ret.) for their recommendations on improving promotion policies in the military.<ref>U.S. Department of Defense, [http://www.defense.gov/speeches/speech.aspx?speechid=1539 \"Speech: As Delivered by Secretary of Defense Robert M. Gates, West Point, NY] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110410130507/http://www.defense.gov/speeches/speech.aspx?speechid=1539 |date=April 10, 2011 }}, 25 February 2011.</ref>\n\nCNAS experts have been quoted in numerous national media outlets, including ''[[Foreign Policy]]'',<ref>See, for example, Robert Kaplan [https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2011/03/01/omans_renaissance_man 'Oman's Renaissance Man'], Foreign Policy, 1 March 2011.</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/03/01/should-the-us-move-against-qaddafi/a-logical-but-difficult-step | work=The New York Times | title=Room for Debate: A Logical, but Difficult, Step | date=March 22, 2011}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/25/AR2011022506229.html | work=The Washington Post | first=Robert D. | last=Kaplan | title=Arab democracy and the return of the Mediterranean world | date=February 27, 2011}}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704050204576218842399053176?mod=googlenews_wsj | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Robert D. | last=Kaplan | title=The Middle East Crisis Has Just Begun | date=March 26, 2011}}</ref> ''[[The National Interest]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nationalinterest.org/article/america-primed-4892|title=America Primed|work=The National Interest}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Show with Jon Stewart]]'',<ref>The Daily Show, [http://www.thedailyshow.com/watch/tue-february-10-2009/thomas-ricks Thomas Ricks], 10 February 2009.</ref> [[C-SPAN]],<ref>C-SPAN, [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/SMilitaryInt/start/0/stop/2706 U.S. Military Intervention in Libya], 23 March 2011.</ref> [[NBC]] and [[MSNBC]],<ref>NBC News, [http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42275424 Meet the Press transcripts], 27 March 2011.</ref> [[Fox News]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://video.foxnews.com/v/5827513707001/|title=President of CNAS Richard Fontaine|website=Fox News}}</ref>, [[NPR]],<ref>Tom Gjelten, [https://www.npr.org/2011/03/24/134807930/in-libyan-conflict-is-endgame-a-stalemate In Libyan Conflict, is Endgame a Stalemate?], NPR, 24 March 2011.</ref> [[CNN]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0910/20/sitroom.03.html | work=CNN | title=CNN.com}}</ref> and [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]].<ref>Center for a New American Security, [http://www.cnas.org/node/5657 United States, Arab Leaders Walk Fine Line as Egypt's Power Center Remains Uncertain] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626024745/http://cnas.org/node/5657 |date=2011-06-26 }}, 4 February 2011.</ref>\n\n== Research and initiatives ==\n[[File:HillaryClintonCNAS.jpg|thumb|[[Hillary Clinton]] speaks at CNAS's rollout event, June 2007]]\n\nCNAS has released extensive reports on terrorism, irregular warfare, and regional security challenges.\n\nBefore joining CNAS, [[John Nagl]] served as an active duty officer in both the first Gulf War and in [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]].  He then was part of the team that wrote FM 3-24, the Army\u2019s [[counter-insurgency]] [[U.S. Army Field Manual|field manual]] that transformed the way the wars in [[Iraq War troop surge of 2007|Iraq]] and [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan]] were conducted. Since joining CNAS first as a Senior Fellow and then as President, Nagl has continued to delve into counterinsurgency while also publishing papers on other topics, including the need for a permanent corps of Army advisers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnas.org/node/130|title=The Pentagon's New Cyber Strategy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100507102403/http://www.cnas.org/node/130|archivedate=2010-05-07}}</ref> and strategies for confronting Islamic extremism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnas.org/node/795|title=Cyberspace Threats Often Blur Government Agency Lines|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612225452/http://cnas.org/node/795|archivedate=2010-06-12}}</ref>\n\nCNAS has also staked out terrain in studying the emergence of [[Asia]] as a center of global power, particularly with regards to [[China]]. One of the main stated goals of CNAS\u2019s Asia-Pacific Security program is to \u201cdevise a future path for America\u2019s engagement of China that can expand bilateral cooperation in areas of shared strategic interest and encourage increasing accountability from the Chinese regime\u201d.<ref>Center for a New American Security, [http://www.cnas.org/asia Asia-Pacific Security] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215194702/http://www.cnas.org/asia |date=2009-12-15 }}</ref>\n\nThe CNAS U.S.-India Initiative is co-chaired by CNAS Board of Directors members [[Richard Armitage (politician)|Richard Armitage]], former Deputy Secretary of State, and Ambassador [[R. Nicholas Burns]], former Under Secretary of State for Political Affairs.  The stated goal of the Initiative is to help advance growing bilateral ties in areas of mutual interest, including security, economics, energy and climate change, democracy and human rights.<ref>Center for a New American Security [http://www.cnas.org/node/3796 India Initiative] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110503224922/http://cnas.org/node/3796 |date=2011-05-03 }}</ref>  On October 27, 2010 at the White House Press Gaggle on the President's Upcoming Trip to India, the CNAS report Natural Allies: A Blueprint for the Future of U.S.-India Relations was referenced in a reporter's question to White House Press Secretary [[Robert Gibbs]].<ref>The White House, Office of the Press Secretary, [http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2010/10/27/press-gaggle-presidents-upcoming-trip-india Press Gaggle on the President's Upcoming Trip to India], 27 October 2010.</ref>\n[[File:Gen. Martin E. Dempsey at New American Security.jpg|thumb|Gen. [[Martin E. Dempsey]] speaking at CNAS, November 2014]]\nIn 2010, the Center developed its Cyber Security project, which is co-chaired by [[Bob Kahn]], the co-inventor of the TCP/IP protocols used to transmit information over the Internet; Vice Admiral [[John Michael McConnell]], USN (Ret.), former Director of National Intelligence; [[Joseph Nye]], Distinguished Service Professor at [[Harvard University]]; and [[Peter Schwartz (futurist)|Peter Schwartz]], a futurist and business strategist and member of the CNAS Board of Directors.<ref>Center for a New American Security [http://www.cnas.org/node/5494 Cyber Security] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501190158/http://www.cnas.org/node/5494 |date=2011-05-01 }}</ref>  In February 2011, CNAS Vice President and Director of Studies Kristin Lord and Research Associate Travis Sharp argued in ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' that \"increased federal attention to cyber security makes good sense,\" but \"lawmakers must ensure that the U.S. government does not spend aimlessly on cyber security.\"<ref>Kristin M. Lord and Travis Sharp, [http://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/economy-a-budget/146189-cyber-sanity Cyber sanity], The Hill, 25 February 2011.</ref>\n\nCNAS has suggested that one way to contain future military costs would be to fold heavy army units into the National guard and reserves, but military officials have responded that the governors would rather have light units, that are better suited to their emergency needs.<ref>Clark, Colin. [http://defense.aol.com/2011/10/07/romney-pledges-defense-boost-analyst-predicts-1-trillion-in-do/ \"Romney Pledges Defense Boost; Analyst Predicts $1 Trillion in DoD Cuts.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425042036/http://defense.aol.com/2011/10/07/romney-pledges-defense-boost-analyst-predicts-1-trillion-in-do/ |date=2012-04-25 }} ''AOL Defense'', 7 October 2011.</ref>\n\n===Papers for the Next President Series===\nIn May 2016, CNAS launched its Papers for the Next President series to assist the next president and his team in crafting a strong, pragmatic, and principled national security agenda. The series explores the most critical regions and topics that the next president will need to address early in his tenure and includes actionable recommendations designed to be implemented during the first few months of 2017. Since its inception, CNAS has released 12 reports<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnas.org/papers-for-the-next-president|title=Preparing the President|website=www.cnas.org}}</ref> on topics including, U.S.-Russia Relations,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Future of U.S.-Russia Relations|url=https://www.cnas.org/publications/reports/the-future-of-u-s-russia-relations|website=Center for a New American Security}}</ref> Transatlantic security cooperation in the Asia-Pacific,<ref>{{cite web|title=Transatlantic Security Cooperation in the Asia-Pacific|url=https://www.cnas.org/publications/reports/transatlantic-security-cooperation-in-the-asia-pacific|website=Center for a New American Security}}</ref> and U.S. strategy in the Middle East.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reset, Negotiate, Institutionalize: A Phased Middle East Strategy for the Next President|url=https://www.cnas.org/publications/reports/reset-negotiate-institutionalize-a-phased-middle-east-strategy-for-the-next-president|website=Center for a New American Security}}</ref>\n\n== Notable scholars and alumni ==\n* [[Richard Armitage (politician)|Richard Armitage]], Assistant Secretary of Defense for International Security Affairs, 1983-1989; Deputy Secretary of State, 2001-2005\n* Shawn Brimley, Director for Strategic Planning, National Security Council, 2010\u20132012\n* [[Kurt M. Campbell]], Assistant Secretary of State for East Asian and Pacific Affairs, 2009\u20132013\n* Lieutenant General [[James Clapper]], USAF (Ret), Director of National Intelligence, 2010\u20132017\n* Dr. Patrick Cronin, Assistant Administrator for Policy and Program Coordination, USAID\n* Abraham Denmark, Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense for East Asia\n* [[Andrew Exum|Dr. Andrew Exum]], Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense for Middle East Policy, 2015\u20132016\n* [[Michele Flournoy]], Under Secretary of Defense for Policy, 2009\u20132012\n* Richard Fontaine, Foreign Policy Advisor to Sen. John McCain (R-AZ), 2002\u20132008\n* [[Colin Kahl]], National Security Advisor to the Vice President, 2014\u20132017\n* [[Robert D. Kaplan]], author and columnist\n* [[Victoria Nuland]], Assistant Secretary of State for European and Eurasian Affairs, 2013\u20132017\n* Dr. Dafna H. Rand, Deputy Assistant Secretary at the U.S. Department of State, 2015\u2013Present\n* Dr. Ely Ratner, Deputy National Security Advisor to the Vice President, 2015\u20132017\n* Admiral [[Gary Roughead]], USN (Ret), [[Chief of Naval Operations]], 2007-2011\n* Loren DeJonge Schulman, Senior Advisor to National Security Advisor Susan Rice, 2013\u20132015\n* Julianne Smith, Deputy National Security Advisor to the Vice President, 2012\u20132013\n* [[Robert O. Work]], Deputy Secretary of Defense, 2014\u20132017\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.cnas.org Center for a New American Security (CNAS)]\n* [https://www.cnas.org/publications CNAS Publications]\n* [https://www.cnas.org/experts CNAS Experts]\n* [https://www.cnas.org/events CNAS Events]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Center For A New American Security}}\n[[Category:Center for a New American Security| ]]\n[[Category:Foreign policy and strategy think tanks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2007]]\n[[Category:Neoconservatism]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox Organization\n| name = Center for a New American Security\n| image = CNAS logo.svg\n| size = \n| abbreviation = CNAS\n| motto = 'Bold. Innovative. Bipartisan'\n| formation = {{start date and age|2007}}\n| type = [[Public policy]] [[think tank]]\n| tax_id = 20-8084828\n| headquarters = 1152 15th St., Ste. 950\n| location = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| leader_title = CEO\n| leader_name = Richard Fontaine<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cnas.org/people/richard-fontaine | title=People | date= | website=Center for a New American Security | accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n| budget = Revenue: $8,789,410<br>Expenses: $7,228,402<br>([[Fiscal year|FYE September 2015]])<ref name=\"Charity ratings\">{{cite web | url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/files.cnas.org/CNAS_Form990_2015a.pdf | title=Center for a New American Security | date=30 September 2016 | website=Amazon Web Services | accessdate=27 February 2017 }}</ref>\n| website = {{url|https://www.cnas.org|CNAS.org}}\n}}[[File:Petraeus1.jpg|thumb|right|GEN [[David Petraeus]] at CNAS's annual conference, June 2009]]\n\nThe '''Center for a New American Security''' ('''CNAS''') is a [[Washington, D.C.]]-based [[think tank]] established in 2007 by co-founders [[Mich\u00e8le Flournoy]] and [[Kurt M. Campbell]]. It specializes in the [[United States]]' [[national security]] issues.  CNAS's stated mission is to \"develop strong, pragmatic and principled national security and defense policies that promote and protect American interests and values.\"<ref>Center for a New American Security, [http://www.cnas.org/about About CNAS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100228145753/http://www.cnas.org/about |date=2010-02-28 }}</ref> CNAS focuses on [[terrorism]] and [[irregular warfare]], the future of the [[U.S. armed forces|U.S. military]], the emergence of [[Asia]] as a global power center, and the national security implications of [[natural]] [[resource consumption]]. Former [[United States Deputy Secretary of State|Deputy Secretary of State]] [[James Steinberg]] called CNAS \"an indispensable feature on the Washington landscape.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/s/d/2009/129686.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091130033804/http://www.state.gov/s/d/2009/129686.htm |archivedate=2009-11-30 }} </ref>  Speaking at the CNAS annual conference in June 2009, [[U.S. Central Command]] Commander GEN [[David Petraeus]] observed that \"CNAS has, in a few years, established itself as a true force in think tank and policy-making circles.\"<ref>Center for a New American Security, [http://www.cnas.org/files/newsletter/CNAS%20About%20Us.pdf 'About the Center for a New American Security] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403123718/http://www.cnas.org/files/newsletter/CNAS%20About%20Us.pdf |date=2015-04-03 }}, 2012.</ref>\n\nThe administration of President [[Barack Obama]] hired several CNAS employees for key jobs.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/05/AR2009060501967.html | work=The Washington Post | title=Carlos Lozada -- Setting Priorities for the Afghan War | date=June 7, 2009 | accessdate=April 28, 2010}}</ref> Founders [[Mich\u00e8le Flournoy]] and [[Kurt M. Campbell|Kurt Campbell]] formerly served as the [[Undersecretary of Defense for Policy]] and the [[Assistant Secretary of State for East Asian and Pacific Affairs]], respectively. In June 2009 ''The Washington Post'' suggested, \"In the era of Obama... the Center for a New American Security may emerge as Washington's go-to think tank on military affairs.\"<ref name=\"post\" />  CNAS scholars have included [[John Nagl]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/01/15/AR2008011503359.html|title=High-Profile Officer Nagl to Leave Army, Join Think Tank | work=The Washington Post | first=Thomas E. | last=Ricks | date=January 16, 2008 | accessdate=April 28, 2010}}</ref> [[David Kilcullen]], [[Andrew Exum]], [[Thomas E. Ricks (journalist)|Thomas E. Ricks]], [[Robert D. Kaplan]],<ref>Center for a New American Security, [http://www.cnas.org/node/71 Robert Kaplan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315080012/http://www.cnas.org/node/71 |date=2011-03-15 }}.</ref> and [[Marc Lynch]]. CNAS is led by CEO [[Victoria Nuland]], who served as the Assistant Secretary of State for European and Eurasian Affairs under Secretary of State [[John Kerry]].\n\nCNAS is relatively small, with around 30 employees and a budget under $6 million.<ref name=\"wsj\">Yochi J. Dreazen, [http://www.livemint.com/2008/11/17175320/Obama-dips-into-think-tank-for.html \"Obama dips into think tank for talent\"], ''The Wall Street Journal'', 18 November 2008</ref> Among the organizations top donors include [[Northrop Grumman Aerospace Systems]], [[Open Society Foundation]], [[Airbus Group]], [[The Boeing Company]], [[Chevron Corporation]], [[Lockheed Martin Corporation]], [[Raytheon Company]], the [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office]],  the United States government, [[BAE Systems]], [[BP America]] and [[Exxon Mobil Corporation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnas.org/support-cnas/cnas-supporters|title=CNAS Supporters|website=www.cnas.org}}</ref>\n\nIn a speech to the [[United States Military Academy]] at [[West Point]] on February 25, 2011, Secretary of Defense [[Robert Gates]] quoted CNAS President [[John Nagl]] and Senior Advisor and Senior Fellow Lieutenant General [[David Barno]], USA (Ret.) for their recommendations on improving promotion policies in the military.<ref>U.S. Department of Defense, [http://www.defense.gov/speeches/speech.aspx?speechid=1539 \"Speech: As Delivered by Secretary of Defense Robert M. Gates, West Point, NY] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110410130507/http://www.defense.gov/speeches/speech.aspx?speechid=1539 |date=April 10, 2011 }}, 25 February 2011.</ref>\n\nCNAS experts have been quoted in numerous national media outlets, including ''[[Foreign Policy]]'',<ref>See, for example, Robert Kaplan [https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2011/03/01/omans_renaissance_man 'Oman's Renaissance Man'], Foreign Policy, 1 March 2011.</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/03/01/should-the-us-move-against-qaddafi/a-logical-but-difficult-step | work=The New York Times | title=Room for Debate: A Logical, but Difficult, Step | date=March 22, 2011}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/25/AR2011022506229.html | work=The Washington Post | first=Robert D. | last=Kaplan | title=Arab democracy and the return of the Mediterranean world | date=February 27, 2011}}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704050204576218842399053176?mod=googlenews_wsj | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Robert D. | last=Kaplan | title=The Middle East Crisis Has Just Begun | date=March 26, 2011}}</ref> ''[[The National Interest]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nationalinterest.org/article/america-primed-4892|title=America Primed|work=The National Interest}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Show with Jon Stewart]]'',<ref>The Daily Show, [http://www.thedailyshow.com/watch/tue-february-10-2009/thomas-ricks Thomas Ricks], 10 February 2009.</ref> [[C-SPAN]],<ref>C-SPAN, [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/SMilitaryInt/start/0/stop/2706 U.S. Military Intervention in Libya], 23 March 2011.</ref> [[NBC]] and [[MSNBC]],<ref>NBC News, [http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42275424 Meet the Press transcripts], 27 March 2011.</ref> [[Fox News]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://video.foxnews.com/v/5827513707001/|title=President of CNAS Richard Fontaine|website=Fox News}}</ref>, [[NPR]],<ref>Tom Gjelten, [https://www.npr.org/2011/03/24/134807930/in-libyan-conflict-is-endgame-a-stalemate In Libyan Conflict, is Endgame a Stalemate?], NPR, 24 March 2011.</ref> [[CNN]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0910/20/sitroom.03.html | work=CNN | title=CNN.com}}</ref> and [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]].<ref>Center for a New American Security, [http://www.cnas.org/node/5657 United States, Arab Leaders Walk Fine Line as Egypt's Power Center Remains Uncertain] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626024745/http://cnas.org/node/5657 |date=2011-06-26 }}, 4 February 2011.</ref>\n\n== Research and initiatives ==\n[[File:HillaryClintonCNAS.jpg|thumb|[[Hillary Clinton]] speaks at CNAS's rollout event, June 2007]]\n\nCNAS has released extensive reports on terrorism, irregular warfare, and regional security challenges.\n\nBefore joining CNAS, [[John Nagl]] served as an active duty officer in both the first Gulf War and in [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]].  He then was part of the team that wrote FM 3-24, the Army\u2019s [[counter-insurgency]] [[U.S. Army Field Manual|field manual]] that transformed the way the wars in [[Iraq War troop surge of 2007|Iraq]] and [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan]] were conducted. Since joining CNAS first as a Senior Fellow and then as President, Nagl has continued to delve into counterinsurgency while also publishing papers on other topics, including the need for a permanent corps of Army advisers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnas.org/node/130|title=The Pentagon's New Cyber Strategy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100507102403/http://www.cnas.org/node/130|archivedate=2010-05-07}}</ref> and strategies for confronting Islamic extremism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnas.org/node/795|title=Cyberspace Threats Often Blur Government Agency Lines|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612225452/http://cnas.org/node/795|archivedate=2010-06-12}}</ref>\n\nCNAS has also staked out terrain in studying the emergence of [[Asia]] as a center of global power, particularly with regards to [[China]]. One of the main stated goals of CNAS\u2019s Asia-Pacific Security program is to \u201cdevise a future path for America\u2019s engagement of China that can expand bilateral cooperation in areas of shared strategic interest and encourage increasing accountability from the Chinese regime\u201d.<ref>Center for a New American Security, [http://www.cnas.org/asia Asia-Pacific Security] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215194702/http://www.cnas.org/asia |date=2009-12-15 }}</ref>\n\nThe CNAS U.S.-India Initiative is co-chaired by CNAS Board of Directors members [[Richard Armitage (politician)|Richard Armitage]], former Deputy Secretary of State, and Ambassador [[R. Nicholas Burns]], former Under Secretary of State for Political Affairs.  The stated goal of the Initiative is to help advance growing bilateral ties in areas of mutual interest, including security, economics, energy and climate change, democracy and human rights.<ref>Center for a New American Security [http://www.cnas.org/node/3796 India Initiative] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110503224922/http://cnas.org/node/3796 |date=2011-05-03 }}</ref>  On October 27, 2010 at the White House Press Gaggle on the President's Upcoming Trip to India, the CNAS report Natural Allies: A Blueprint for the Future of U.S.-India Relations was referenced in a reporter's question to White House Press Secretary [[Robert Gibbs]].<ref>The White House, Office of the Press Secretary, [http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2010/10/27/press-gaggle-presidents-upcoming-trip-india Press Gaggle on the President's Upcoming Trip to India], 27 October 2010.</ref>\n[[File:Gen. Martin E. Dempsey at New American Security.jpg|thumb|Gen. [[Martin E. Dempsey]] speaking at CNAS, November 2014]]\nIn 2010, the Center developed its Cyber Security project, which is co-chaired by [[Bob Kahn]], the co-inventor of the TCP/IP protocols used to transmit information over the Internet; Vice Admiral [[John Michael McConnell]], USN (Ret.), former Director of National Intelligence; [[Joseph Nye]], Distinguished Service Professor at [[Harvard University]]; and [[Peter Schwartz (futurist)|Peter Schwartz]], a futurist and business strategist and member of the CNAS Board of Directors.<ref>Center for a New American Security [http://www.cnas.org/node/5494 Cyber Security] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501190158/http://www.cnas.org/node/5494 |date=2011-05-01 }}</ref>  In February 2011, CNAS Vice President and Director of Studies Kristin Lord and Research Associate Travis Sharp argued in ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' that \"increased federal attention to cyber security makes good sense,\" but \"lawmakers must ensure that the U.S. government does not spend aimlessly on cyber security.\"<ref>Kristin M. Lord and Travis Sharp, [http://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/economy-a-budget/146189-cyber-sanity Cyber sanity], The Hill, 25 February 2011.</ref>\n\nCNAS has suggested that one way to contain future military costs would be to fold heavy army units into the National guard and reserves, but military officials have responded that the governors would rather have light units, that are better suited to their emergency needs.<ref>Clark, Colin. [http://defense.aol.com/2011/10/07/romney-pledges-defense-boost-analyst-predicts-1-trillion-in-do/ \"Romney Pledges Defense Boost; Analyst Predicts $1 Trillion in DoD Cuts.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425042036/http://defense.aol.com/2011/10/07/romney-pledges-defense-boost-analyst-predicts-1-trillion-in-do/ |date=2012-04-25 }} ''AOL Defense'', 7 October 2011.</ref>\n\n===Papers for the Next President Series===\nIn May 2016, CNAS launched its Papers for the Next President series to assist the next president and his team in crafting a strong, pragmatic, and principled national security agenda. The series explores the most critical regions and topics that the next president will need to address early in his tenure and includes actionable recommendations designed to be implemented during the first few months of 2017. Since its inception, CNAS has released 12 reports<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnas.org/papers-for-the-next-president|title=Preparing the President|website=www.cnas.org}}</ref> on topics including, U.S.-Russia Relations,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Future of U.S.-Russia Relations|url=https://www.cnas.org/publications/reports/the-future-of-u-s-russia-relations|website=Center for a New American Security}}</ref> Transatlantic security cooperation in the Asia-Pacific,<ref>{{cite web|title=Transatlantic Security Cooperation in the Asia-Pacific|url=https://www.cnas.org/publications/reports/transatlantic-security-cooperation-in-the-asia-pacific|website=Center for a New American Security}}</ref> and U.S. strategy in the Middle East.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reset, Negotiate, Institutionalize: A Phased Middle East Strategy for the Next President|url=https://www.cnas.org/publications/reports/reset-negotiate-institutionalize-a-phased-middle-east-strategy-for-the-next-president|website=Center for a New American Security}}</ref>\n\n== Notable scholars and alumni ==\n* [[Richard Armitage (politician)|Richard Armitage]], Assistant Secretary of Defense for International Security Affairs, 1983-1989; Deputy Secretary of State, 2001-2005\n* Shawn Brimley, Director for Strategic Planning, National Security Council, 2010\u20132012\n* [[Kurt M. Campbell]], Assistant Secretary of State for East Asian and Pacific Affairs, 2009\u20132013\n* Lieutenant General [[James Clapper]], USAF (Ret), Director of National Intelligence, 2010\u20132017\n* Dr. Patrick Cronin, Assistant Administrator for Policy and Program Coordination, USAID\n* Abraham Denmark, Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense for East Asia\n* [[Andrew Exum|Dr. Andrew Exum]], Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense for Middle East Policy, 2015\u20132016\n* [[Michele Flournoy]], Under Secretary of Defense for Policy, 2009\u20132012\n* Richard Fontaine, Foreign Policy Advisor to Sen. John McCain (R-AZ), 2002\u20132008\n* Colin Kahl, National Security Advisor to the Vice President, 2014\u20132017\n* [[Robert D. Kaplan]], author and columnist\n* [[Victoria Nuland]], Assistant Secretary of State for European and Eurasian Affairs, 2013\u20132017\n* Dr. Dafna H. Rand, Deputy Assistant Secretary at the U.S. Department of State, 2015\u2013Present\n* Dr. Ely Ratner, Deputy National Security Advisor to the Vice President, 2015\u20132017\n* Admiral [[Gary Roughead]], USN (Ret), [[Chief of Naval Operations]], 2007-2011\n* Loren DeJonge Schulman, Senior Advisor to National Security Advisor Susan Rice, 2013\u20132015\n* Julianne Smith, Deputy National Security Advisor to the Vice President, 2012\u20132013\n* [[Robert O. Work]], Deputy Secretary of Defense, 2014\u20132017\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.cnas.org Center for a New American Security (CNAS)]\n* [https://www.cnas.org/publications CNAS Publications]\n* [https://www.cnas.org/experts CNAS Experts]\n* [https://www.cnas.org/events CNAS Events]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Center For A New American Security}}\n[[Category:Center for a New American Security| ]]\n[[Category:Foreign policy and strategy think tanks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2007]]\n[[Category:Neoconservatism]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "WhinyTheYounger", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable scholars and alumni:Link add: Colin Kahl", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Center_for_a_New_American_Security"}
